# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
For every element we come across in the given array, we are faced with the choice of either picking it to subtract from the target, or not picking it. 

Using this fact, we can traverse the given array and make recursive calls to the function for each element in the array, reducing the target by the value picked till either the index is equal to size of the array or the value of target reaches less than or equal to zero.

If target value reaches zero, it means that the combination of elements picked will add up to the target and is a valid solution.

**NOTE:** Since this problem allows us to pick multiple instances of the same element, we will pass the current index of the array (instead of the next one) when recursively calling the function as we can choose to pick it again.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Pass 0, `target`, `candidates`, `temp` and `sol` to the function `genUniqueCombos` that will generate unique combinations of the numbers adding up to the target. The parameters passed represent the current index, target to be attained, given array, array holding possible combination and array holding all possible combinations respectively.

If the index we are currently at is less than or equal to the target, we can think about adding it to (one of possible) solution. Push it into `temp` and recursively call the function, only this time with target reduced by the element added.

Once function call is returned, remove the element added to `temp`.

If index we are currently at is greater than the target, we cannot add it to the solution. Simply recursively call the function with the next index.

We can set the base case as the current index becoming equal to the size of the array, or the target becoming less than or equal to zero. If the target is equal to zero, we can surely say that it is one of the possible solutions and can push it into `sol`.

**PS:** Recursion tree for `candidates` = [1, 2, 3] and `target` = 3.

![WhatsApp Image 2023-05-14 at 8.23.53 AM.jpeg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/2c69be16-4196-4f42-9865-c93fbb4c1fb7_1684032984.0102649.jpeg)


# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(k*2^t)$$, where k is the number of possible solutions and t is the target to be attained.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(k*x)$$, where k is number of possible solutions and x is the size of the longest solution.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    void genUniqueCombos(int idx, int target, vector<int>& candidates, vector<int>& temp, vector<vector<int>>& sol){
        if(idx==candidates.size()||target<=0){
            if(!target) sol.push_back(temp);
            return;
        }

        if(candidates[idx]<=target){
            temp.push_back(candidates[idx]);
            genUniqueCombos(idx, target-candidates[idx], candidates, temp, sol);
            temp.pop_back();
        }
        genUniqueCombos(idx+1, target, candidates, temp, sol);
    }

    vector<vector<int>> combinationSum(vector<int>& candidates, int target) {
        vector<int> temp;
        vector<vector<int>> sol;

        genUniqueCombos(0, target, candidates, temp, sol);
        return sol;
    }
};

```

